<p><ent>Him</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Him
<hw>Him</hw>, <pos>pron.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>him</ets>, dat. of
<ets>h⟦emac⟧</ets>. ⟦root⟧183. See <er>He</er>.]</ety> <def>The
objective case of <xex>he</xex>. See <er>He</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Him</qex> that is weak in the faith receive.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. xiv. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Friends who have given <qex>him</qex> the most sympathy.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In old English <xex>his</xex> and <xex>him</xex> were
respectively the genitive and dative forms of <xex>it</xex> as well as
of <xex>he</xex>. <xex>This use is now obsolete</xex>.
<xex>Poetically</xex>, <xex>him</xex> is sometimes used with the
reflexive sense of <xex>himself</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I never saw but Humphrey, duke of Gloster,⟦br⟧
Did bear <qex>him</qex> like a noble gentleman.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Himalayan</ent>⟦br⟧
